Interviewer: To start, I would like to begin with a big question: tell me the story of your life. Start from the beginning -- from your childhood, to education, to family and relationships, and to any major life events you may have had.

Jessica Gonzalez: I was born in Mexico, but I moved to the United States when I was about five years old. My family settled in Minneapolis, and I've lived here ever since. Growing up, I was really close to my parents, who both have graduate degrees, which I think influenced my love for learning. My mom worked full-time, and my dad worked from home, so I grew up in a household that valued education and hard work. I was raised Catholic, but as I got older, I found myself less connected to religion. I speak Spanish at home, and I'm proud of that part of my heritage. I'm currently in school, working toward my degree, and I hope to one day make a difference in my community. Life hasn't been easy—money has always been tight, and I've had to work part-time while going to school—but I've always believed that education is the key to a better future.

Interviewer: Some people tell us that they've reached a crossroads at some points in their life where multiple paths were available, and their choice then made a significant difference in defining who they are. What about you? Was there a moment like that for you, and if so, could you tell me the whole story about that from start to finish?

Jessica Gonzalez: There was a moment in high school when I had to decide whether to take the easier path and go to a community college close to home or apply to a more competitive university that would challenge me more, even if it meant moving away from my family. I was really torn because I didn't want to leave my parents, especially since we weren't in a great financial position. But I also knew that if I stayed close, I might not get the opportunities I needed to grow. I remember talking to my mom late one night, and she said, 'If you want something more, you have to be willing to work for it.' That really stuck with me. I applied to a few schools, got into one that offered a scholarship, and I took the leap. It wasn't easy—missing my family, adjusting to a new environment, and managing school and work all at once—but that experience shaped who I am today. It taught me resilience, independence, and the importance of believing in myself even when things feel uncertain.

Interviewer: Some people tell us they made a conscious choice or decision in moments like these, while others say it 'just happened'. What about you?

Jessica Gonzalez: I think it was a conscious choice, but not one I made easily. I had to weigh so many things—my family, my finances, my future. I didn't just wake up one day and decide to leave; it was a lot of late-night conversations, a lot of doubt, and a lot of hope. I remember sitting at my kitchen table, looking at the acceptance letter, and realizing that this was my chance to build something for myself. I made a list of all the 'what-ifs' and 'what-ifs' kept me up at night. But in the end, I chose to take the risk because I believed in the possibility of something better. I think that's what makes a choice conscious—it's not just about the decision itself, but the weight you carry when you make it.

Interviewer: Do you think another person or an organization could have lent a helping hand during moments like this?

Jessica Gonzalez: Absolutely. I think if I had reached out to a counselor at my high school or even connected with a mentor in my community, it might have made the decision a little easier. I was pretty shy back then, and I didn't want to burden anyone with my worries. But looking back, I realize how much support I could have had. There was a local nonprofit that helped students apply for scholarships, and I remember seeing their flyers, but I didn't have the confidence to walk in. I wish I had taken that step. Sometimes, the people and organizations around us have the tools we need—we just need the courage to ask for help.

Interviewer: Moving to present time, tell me more about family who are important to you. Do you have a partner, or children?

Jessica Gonzalez: Right now, I don't have a partner or children. My family is still my main support system, especially my parents. They've been through a lot with me—supporting me through school, helping me with expenses when I could barely afford rent, and always reminding me that I'm capable of more than I sometimes believe. My mom still works full-time, and my dad is a teacher at a local school, which I think is why he always encouraged me to pursue education. I have a younger sister who's in high school, and we're really close. She's the one who actually pushed me to apply for that scholarship I mentioned earlier. She saw something in me that I didn't see in myself. Even though I'm away from home now, I try to stay connected with them as much as I can. I know my future will be brighter because of them, and I hope to be there for them in the same way when they need me.

Going through those interview questions felt like revisiting key moments that shaped who I am today. Talking about my life story reminded me of how far I've come, from growing up in Minneapolis to making the tough decision to leave home for a better education. It was hard to relive the doubts and fears I had back then, but it also reminded me of the strength I found within myself. Reflecting on the support I received—and the support I didn't ask for—made me realize how much I owe to my family and the people who believed in me. Even though I didn't have everything, I always had the will to keep going. And now, as I continue working toward my degree, I carry that same determination with me, knowing that every step I take is a step toward making a difference—not just for myself, but for my family and my community.

Interviewer: Are there anyone else in your immediate family whom you have not mentioned? Who are they, and what is your relationship with them like?

Jessica Gonzalez: My grandparents are still in Mexico, and I talk to them often, especially on weekends. They've always been a big part of my life, even though I haven't been able to visit them in person since I moved to the U.S. My abuela, in particular, has been a huge influence on me. She's the one who taught me to cook traditional dishes and to value family above all else. Even though we're separated by distance, she's always been there for me, sending care packages with food and letters filled with advice. My grandpa, on the other hand, is more of a quiet presence—always listening, always watching. He used to tell me stories about growing up in Mexico, and I think those stories helped me feel connected to my roots, even when I was struggling to find my place here. I miss them a lot, but I know that my connection to them is what keeps me grounded, especially when things get tough.

Interviewer: Tell me about anyone else in your life we haven’t discussed (like friends or romantic partners). Are there people outside of your family who are important to you?

Jessica Gonzalez: Outside of my family, I have a few close friends who have been there for me through thick and thin. One of them, Maria, is actually someone I met in college. We bonded over our shared experiences as first-generation students and the pressure we felt to make our families proud. She's become like a sister to me, and we've supported each other through late-night study sessions, job searches, and even moments of self-doubt. There's also a group of friends from my hometown that I still keep in touch with—some of them are in the same boat as me, trying to make it through school while working part-time. I think what makes these relationships so important is that they remind me I'm not alone in this journey. Even though I'm focused on my own goals, knowing that there are people who understand what I'm going through gives me strength. I don't know where I'd be without them.

Interviewer: Now let’s talk about your current neighborhood. Tell me all about the neighborhood and area in which you are living now.

Jessica Gonzalez: I live in a neighborhood in Minneapolis that's pretty diverse, with a mix of long-time residents and newer folks like myself. It's a bit on the quieter side, with a lot of tree-lined streets and small businesses that give the area a community feel. There's a local library nearby that I go to often—it's a quiet place to study, and they have a lot of resources for students like me. I also live in an apartment complex that's pretty affordable, though it's not the most luxurious. The building has a small courtyard where people gather, and I've gotten to know some of my neighbors. Some of them are students too, and others are working professionals. I like that there's a sense of shared purpose here, even if we're all in different stages of life. It's not perfect—there are days when the noise from the street or the lack of space feels overwhelming—but overall, I feel like this neighborhood has given me a sense of stability while I work toward my goals.

Interviewer: Some people say they feel really safe in their neighborhoods, others not so much. How about for you?

Jessica Gonzalez: I feel pretty safe here, honestly. There's a sense of community that makes the neighborhood feel like a place where people look out for one another. I've never had any real issues with crime or feeling unsafe, which is something I'm grateful for. That said, I know not everyone feels the same way, especially if they're from a different background or don't have the same resources as I do. I think safety is something that depends a lot on where you live and who you know. For me, the fact that there are so many students and young professionals in the area gives me a sense of hope—that this is a place where people are working toward something, and that kind of energy makes me feel more secure, even if I'm not always sure about the future.

Interviewer: Living any place has its ups and downs. Tell me about what it’s been like for you living here.

Jessica Gonzalez: Living here has had its challenges, but also a lot of rewards. On the positive side, the sense of community is something I really appreciate. I've met people from all walks of life, and it's amazing how we can come together over shared goals, like education or just wanting to make the best of our circumstances. The library is a big part of my routine, and I've even started volunteering there a few days a week, which has been really fulfilling. It gives me a chance to give back, and it also helps me stay connected to my purpose. That said, there are days when I feel the weight of everything I'm trying to balance—school, work, rent, and the constant pressure to do better. I don't have a lot of extra money, so sometimes I have to make tough choices, like skipping meals to afford books or sacrificing sleep to finish an assignment. But I try to remind myself that these are just temporary struggles, and that every small step I take is moving me closer to something bigger. I know it's not easy, but I also know I'm not alone in this. And that makes all the difference.

Going through the interview questions about my family and current neighborhood reminded me of how much my roots and surroundings shape who I am. Talking about my parents, sister, and grandparents made me realize how much they've sacrificed and supported me, even when things were tough. It also made me appreciate the sense of community in my neighborhood—how even in a place that's not perfect, there's a shared understanding and purpose that helps people like me keep going. I think it's important to remember where you come from and who has helped you along the way, because that's what gives you the strength to keep moving forward, even when the path isn't easy.

Interviewer: Right now, across a typical week, how do your days vary?

Jessica Gonzalez: A typical week for me is pretty structured, but it's also full of surprises. I usually start my week on Monday with a big cup of coffee and a quick breakfast before heading to class. I'm enrolled in a full-time program, so my days are packed with lectures, group projects, and readings. After class, I work part-time at a local bookstore, which I actually enjoy because it's a calm environment and I get to interact with people who love books as much as I do. Tuesdays and Wednesdays are usually the busiest days for me—more assignments, more meetings, and sometimes even a bit of overtime at work. Thursdays are my favorite because I have a study group in the evening, and we meet at the library. It's a great way to stay on track and support each other. Fridays are usually a bit more relaxed, and I try to spend time with friends or call my family. On weekends, I either catch up on chores, do some volunteering at the library, or just take a walk around the neighborhood to clear my head. It's not always easy balancing everything, but I've learned to make the most of every moment, even the busy ones.

Interviewer: At what kind of job or jobs do you work, and when do you work?

Jessica Gonzalez: I work part-time at a local bookstore, usually on weekdays after my classes. My shifts are in the afternoons, from around 2:00 PM to 6:00 PM, which gives me enough time to get to class in the morning and still have some time to study in the evenings. The job isn't glamorous, but I enjoy it because it's a calm place to be, and I get to meet people who share my love for books. It also helps me stay connected to my community, and I feel good about supporting a small business. Sometimes, I help organize events at the store, like author readings or book clubs, which has been a nice way to give back and use my skills. I know it's not much, but every dollar I earn helps me stay in school and keep my head above water. It's a small part of my journey, but it's one I'm proud of.

Interviewer: Do you have other routines or responsibilities that you did not already share?

Jessica Gonzalez: Outside of work and school, I also have a routine of taking care of my younger sister when my parents are busy. She's in high school, and she's been going through a lot with her own academic pressures and figuring out who she wants to be. I try to help her with her homework when I can, and sometimes we just talk about our fears and dreams. It's a big responsibility, but it also reminds me why I'm working so hard—to be there for her and to show her that it's possible to build a better life, even with the challenges we face. I also try to stay active by going for runs in the park near my apartment, even if it's just for 20 minutes. It helps me clear my mind and stay focused. And every Sunday, I make sure to call my grandparents in Mexico. We talk about everything—how the weather is, what's happening in our lives, and sometimes just sit in silence for a while. Those calls are my anchor, reminding me of where I came from and the love that's always been there for me.

Interviewer: Tell me about any recent changes to your daily routine.

Jessica Gonzalez: One recent change to my daily routine has been starting to incorporate more mindfulness practices, like meditation and journaling, to help manage the stress that comes with balancing school, work, and family. I've been feeling the pressure more than usual lately, especially with upcoming exams and a big project due soon. I found a short meditation app that I use during my breaks at work, and I've started writing in a journal every morning before I get out of bed. It's been a small but meaningful shift—it helps me center myself and reminds me of why I'm doing all of this. I also started taking a few online courses on time management and self-care, which have been really helpful. It's funny, though, because I used to think that being busy meant being productive, but now I realize that taking a moment to breathe or reflect is just as important as pushing through every task. I'm still learning how to find that balance, but I feel like these changes are helping me stay grounded and focused on the bigger picture.

Interviewer: If you have children, tell me about a typical weekday during the school year for your children. What is their daily routine? And what are after school activities your children participate in?

Jessica Gonzalez: I don't have children yet, but I often imagine what life would be like if I did. I think a typical weekday for my children would involve waking up early, having a healthy breakfast, and then heading off to school. I'd make sure they had everything they needed for the day—lunch, snacks, and any homework they might have. After school, they'd probably have some time to relax, maybe play with friends or do something they enjoy, like sports or music. I'd love to be involved in their after-school activities, whether it's helping with homework, attending a game, or just being there to listen when they need to talk. I know raising kids would be a huge responsibility, but I also know it would be one of the most rewarding things I could do. For now, I'm focused on building a strong foundation for my own future so that I can be there for them when the time comes.

Going through the interview questions from 11 to 15 made me reflect on how deeply my family, neighborhood, and daily routines shape my identity and purpose. Talking about my family reminded me of the sacrifices they've made and the unconditional support they've given me, even when things were tough. It also made me realize how much I owe them and how I want to be there for my sister the way they've always been there for me. Thinking about my neighborhood brought back the sense of community I feel here, even in the small ways—like the quiet library where I study or the friendly neighbors who share a smile. It reminded me that I'm not alone in this journey, and that sense of connection is what keeps me going. When I talked about my daily routines, I saw how much I've grown in balancing school, work, and family, but I also saw how much I still have to learn about taking care of myself. It's easy to get caught up in the hustle, but I'm starting to understand that self-care and mindfulness are just as important as pushing forward. These reflections made me realize that while my path hasn't been easy, it's been shaped by the people I love, the community I'm part of, and the small but meaningful choices I make every day.

Interviewer: Now we’d like to learn more about your health. First, tell me all about your health.

Jessica Gonzalez: My health has been something I've had to be pretty mindful of, especially with everything else going on. I try to stay as active as I can, like running in the park a few times a week, but there are days when stress or exhaustion makes it hard to keep up with that. I've also been dealing with some anxiety, especially when things feel overwhelming—like during exam season or when I'm juggling too many responsibilities at once. I've started seeing a counselor through the university, and that's been really helpful. Talking through my worries has made a big difference, and I've learned some coping strategies that help me stay grounded. I also try to eat healthy when I can, but with a tight budget, it's not always easy. Sometimes I have to choose between buying groceries or paying for textbooks. I know my health is important, and I'm trying to take it more seriously now, even if it's one step at a time.

Interviewer: For you, what makes it easy or hard to stay healthy?

Jessica Gonzalez: What makes it easy to stay healthy is knowing that even small things matter—like taking a walk, eating a balanced meal, or just getting enough sleep. I've started setting little goals for myself, like drinking more water or going to bed 15 minutes earlier, and those tiny changes add up. But what makes it hard is the constant pressure of everything else—school, work, family responsibilities. Sometimes, I feel like I don't have time to take care of myself, and that guilt can be overwhelming. I also struggle with access to affordable healthcare and healthy food options, which makes it harder to prioritize my well-being. But I'm learning that staying healthy isn't about perfection—it's about showing up for myself, even on the tough days, and recognizing that my health is just as important as my education or my future.

Interviewer: Tell me about anything big that has happened in the past two years related to your health: any medical diagnoses, flare-ups of chronic conditions, broken bones, pain – anything like that.

Jessica Gonzalez: In the past two years, I've dealt with a few health challenges that have tested my strength. The biggest thing was when I started experiencing persistent back pain, probably from sitting for long hours during classes and work. At first, I tried to ignore it, thinking it would go away on its own, but it got worse over time. I finally went to the campus health center, and they diagnosed me with a mild spinal strain. It was a wake-up call—I realized I hadn't been taking care of my body the way I should have. I started seeing a physical therapist, and I've been doing some exercises to strengthen my core and improve my posture. It's been a slow process, but I'm getting better. Along with that, I've also been dealing with occasional migraines, especially during stressful periods. I think the combination of stress, lack of sleep, and not eating regularly has contributed to that. I've started keeping a journal to track when the migraines happen and what triggers them, which has helped me manage them a bit better. It's been tough, but I'm learning that taking care of my health is just as important as everything else I'm trying to accomplish. I can't keep going if I'm not taking care of myself first.

Interviewer: Sometimes, health problems get in the way. They can even affect people’s ability to work or care for their children. How about you?

Jessica Gonzalez: Honestly, there have been moments when my health issues made it harder to keep up with everything—like when the back pain got so bad that I had to take a few days off from work and class. It was frustrating because I felt like I was falling behind, and I didn't want to let my family or my studies down. I also worried that if I didn't push through, I'd be setting a bad example for my sister. But what I've learned is that taking a break isn't a failure—it's part of the process. I've had to be more intentional about pacing myself, listening to my body, and not trying to do everything at once. It's not always easy, but I'm starting to see that taking care of my health isn't just about avoiding pain; it's about being able to show up for the people I love and the goals I care about. I know I can't do it all at once, but I'm trying to do it all with more care and less guilt.

Interviewer: Now we’re going to talk a bit more about what life was like for you over the past year. Tell me all about how you have been feeling.

Jessica Gonzalez: Over the past year, I've felt a mix of emotions—there's been a lot of growth, but also a lot of challenges. I've learned to be more honest with myself about what I can handle and what I need to let go of. There were times when I felt overwhelmed, especially when I was juggling school, work, and taking care of my sister. But I've also felt a deep sense of purpose, especially when I'm helping others at the library or when I'm supporting my family. I think I've become more resilient, and I've started to believe in my own strength more than I used to. I'm still figuring things out, but I feel like I'm on the right path, even if it's not always easy.

Going through the interview questions from 16 to 20 made me reflect on how much my health and well-being have been intertwined with the rest of my life. It reminded me that even though I've been focused on school, work, and family, I can't neglect my own health. The recent changes I've made, like incorporating mindfulness and journaling, have been small but meaningful steps toward taking better care of myself. It also made me realize how much stress and responsibility can take a toll on the body and mind, and how important it is to listen to my body when it's asking for rest. I used to think that pushing through was the only way to succeed, but now I see that taking care of my health is just as vital as everything else I'm trying to achieve. These reflections have helped me understand that I don't have to be perfect—I just need to be present and intentional with my choices, even when life feels overwhelming.

Interviewer: Some people say they struggle with depression, anxiety, or something else like that. How about for you?

Jessica Gonzalez: I think I've struggled with anxiety more than anything else, especially when things feel out of control or when I'm overwhelmed with responsibilities. There were times when I would lie awake at night, worrying about whether I was doing enough for my family, whether I was going to fail my classes, or whether I was making the right choices for my future. It's not something I used to talk about openly, but I've started to realize that it's okay to not be okay. I've been working with a counselor at the university, and that's been a huge help. She's taught me how to recognize when my anxiety is creeping in and how to manage it before it takes over. I've also started using grounding techniques, like deep breathing or focusing on the present moment, which has made a difference. I don't think I'll ever be completely free of anxiety, but I'm learning to live with it instead of letting it define me. It's a process, but I'm grateful for the tools I've gained—it's helped me feel more in control of my life, even when everything else feels uncertain.

Interviewer: How has it been for your family?

Jessica Gonzalez: For my family, it's been a mix of pride, worry, and support. My parents have always believed in me, even when things felt impossible. They've sacrificed so much to give me the chance to be here, and I know they're proud of the work I'm doing, but they also worry about the stress I'm under. My mom, in particular, has been talking to me more about her own fears—about whether I'm eating enough, whether I'm getting enough sleep, and whether I'm taking care of myself. She doesn't want me to burn out the way she did in her own career. My dad, on the other hand, is more focused on encouraging me to keep going, reminding me that I'm capable of more than I sometimes believe. My sister has been my biggest cheerleader, though. She's been through her own struggles, and she knows what it's like to feel like you're fighting an uphill battle. She texts me every day, just to check in, and sometimes we talk for hours about our dreams and fears. Even though we're all dealing with our own challenges, I think we're all learning to support each other in new ways. It's not always easy, but I feel like we're growing together, even if we're not always sure where we're headed.

Interviewer: Some people say that religion or spirituality is important in their lives, for others not so much. How about you?

Jessica Gonzalez: I think I've always had a complicated relationship with religion. Growing up, I was raised Catholic, and my family attended church regularly. It was a part of our lives, and I remember feeling a sense of comfort in the rituals and the community. But as I got older, I started to question a lot of things—why certain things happened, why the world was the way it was, and whether faith was enough to explain it all. I didn't walk away from it suddenly; it was more of a slow shift. I stopped going to church, and over time, I stopped identifying as Catholic. Now, I don't really think of myself as religious, but I do believe in something bigger than myself. I think of it more as a personal spirituality—like the idea that we're all connected, and that love, kindness, and resilience are what matter most. I don't need a church to feel that, and I think that's what makes me who I am today. I respect my roots, but I also respect the freedom to find my own path.

Interviewer: Some people tell us they use Facebook, Instagram, or other social media to stay connected with the wider world. How about for you? Tell me all about how you use these types of platforms.

Jessica Gonzalez: I use social media mostly to stay connected with my family and friends, especially since I can't visit my grandparents in Mexico as often as I'd like. I have a Facebook page where I post pictures of my day-to-day life, like my study sessions at the library or the runs I take in the park. My mom and sister love seeing those posts because it helps them feel closer to me, even though we're not together. I also use Instagram to follow some educational accounts that share tips on time management and self-care, which have been really helpful for me. I don't post much myself, but I do enjoy scrolling through stories and seeing what my friends are up to. Sometimes, I'll message my sister or my friends on WhatsApp to catch up, especially when I'm feeling overwhelmed. It's not the same as being in person, but it helps me feel less alone. I think social media has its ups and downs—there are days when I get lost in the noise or compare myself to others—but overall, I'm grateful for the ways it helps me stay connected to the people who matter most.

Interviewer: Some people say they use Facebook or Twitter to get (emotional or financial) support during tough times. What about you?

Jessica Gonzalez: Honestly, I haven't used social media much for emotional or financial support, but I know it could be a tool for people in similar situations. I think the biggest way it's helped me is through staying connected with my family and friends, especially when I'm feeling down. My sister and I often message each other on WhatsApp when things get tough, and just knowing she's there gives me strength. I've also seen some posts from other students who are going through the same struggles—balancing school, work, and family—and it's comforting to know I'm not alone in this. I don't think I'd ever ask for financial help online, but I do appreciate the sense of community that social media can create. It's not perfect, but it's a way to feel supported when life feels overwhelming.

Going through the interview questions from 21 to 25 made me reflect deeply on my health and the emotional challenges I've faced over the past year. It reminded me how much my body and mind have been tested by the constant demands of school, work, and family. I used to think that pushing through pain or anxiety was the only way to show strength, but now I see that taking care of myself is just as important as anything else. Talking about my back pain and migraines made me realize how much I've ignored my body's signals, and how much I need to listen to them more carefully. It also made me think about my anxiety—how it's been a constant companion, especially during stressful times. But instead of letting it define me, I'm learning to manage it, to recognize when I need to pause and breathe. I'm grateful for the support of my family and the tools I've gained through counseling, because they've helped me see that my health isn't a weakness, but a foundation. I can't build a better future for myself or my family if I'm not taking care of the most important part of me first.

Interviewer: Tell me about any recent changes in your level of stress, worry, and your emotional coping strategies.

Jessica Gonzalez: In the past few months, I've noticed my stress levels have been a bit higher than usual, probably because I'm juggling more responsibilities than ever before. I've been trying to manage my schoolwork, my part-time job, taking care of my sister, and even volunteering at the library. It's a lot, and there are days when I feel like I'm running on empty. But I've been working on my emotional coping strategies, too. I've started journaling more regularly, not just for mindfulness but also to process my feelings when things get overwhelming. I also try to practice deep breathing when I feel my anxiety creeping in, and I've been more intentional about setting boundaries—like saying no to extra work when I need to rest. I've even started talking to my counselor more often, which has been really helpful. She's taught me that it's okay to feel stressed, but it's also important to find ways to release that pressure before it builds up too much. I'm still learning, but I feel like I'm getting better at recognizing when I need to slow down and take a step back, even if it's just for a few minutes.

Interviewer: Now we’d like to talk about how you make ends meet and what the monthly budget looks like for you and your family. What were your biggest expenses last month?

Jessica Gonzalez: Last month, my biggest expenses were rent, groceries, and tuition. Rent is the largest chunk of my budget—my apartment is affordable, but it still takes up about half of what I earn from my part-time job and any financial help my parents can give. Groceries are another challenge because I try to eat healthy, but with a tight budget, I often have to buy in bulk or choose cheaper options, which can be tricky when I need to make sure I'm getting enough nutrients. Tuition is something I pay for through a combination of scholarships, grants, and a small loan I took out, so that's a fixed cost every month. I also have to set aside money for books and transportation, which adds up. What's interesting is that I've started tracking my expenses more closely, and it's helped me see where I can cut back, like eating out less or buying secondhand textbooks. It's not easy, but I'm learning to be more intentional with every dollar I spend, knowing that it's all part of building a better future for myself and my family.

Interviewer: How much did your household spend in the past month? Is that the usual amount? And if not, how much do you usually spend and on what?

Jessica Gonzalez: Our household spending last month was around $2,200, which is pretty much in line with what we usually spend. The majority of that goes to rent, which is about $1,000 a month, and groceries, which hover around $500. Tuition and fees are another $600, and then there's about $100 for books and supplies, plus transportation and miscellaneous expenses. It's not a lot, but it's enough to get by, especially since my parents still help out when they can. I've been trying to be more careful with every dollar, like buying secondhand clothes or using public transportation instead of Uber when I can. It's a tight budget, but I know it's temporary. I'm working toward a future where I can afford more stability—not just for myself, but for my family too. I've learned that every little bit counts, and even small sacrifices now can lead to bigger opportunities later.

Interviewer: Does your household own or rent your home?
